description: From fog +‎ -y, originally in the sense "covered with tall grass; marshy; thick". It is not clear whether fog (“mist”) is a back-formation from foggy (“covered with tall, obscuring grass”) or has a separate Germanic origin, and hence whether foggy (“covered with tall grass”) and foggy (“obscured by mist”) represent one word or two. See fog ("mist"; "tall grass") for more.

entries.meaning: Obscured by mist or fog; unclear; hazy

examples: He was still foggy with sleep.

entries.meaning: Being, covered with, or pertaining to fog (“tall grass etc that grows after, or is left after, cutting; moss”)
examples: For they will feed on foggy grass and such like. Also ye shall understand that horses and Cattel may not well be foddered in Winter all together, but  […]
